        "Applying ML algorithms means matching the right model family to the task, training it correctly, and validating that it generalizes — not just picking an algorithm name and running it once. Common algorithm families include linear regression and logistic regression (for continuous and binary/categorical targets respectively), decision trees (which split data based on feature values to form a tree of decisions), k-nearest neighbors (k-NN, which classifies a point based on the majority vote of its k closest neighbors in feature space), and neural networks (layered networks of weighted connections that can model complex, non-linear relationships). To get reliable estimates of how a model will perform on new data, practitioners use cross-validation — rotating which portion of the data is held out as validation across multiple training runs — rather than relying on a single train/test split. Hyperparameters (settings chosen before training, such as k in k-NN or the depth of a decision tree) are tuned using validation data, never the test set, to avoid leaking information about final performance into the tuning process. Regularization techniques (such as L1 and L2 penalties) discourage overly complex models, directly combating overfitting, while ensemble methods (bagging, boosting, random forests) combine multiple models to improve robustness and accuracy beyond what any single model achieves alone.",
