          body: "Suppose we want to classify a new point P based on its 5 nearest labeled neighbors, but we set k=3, so only the 3 closest matter. Their distances to P and labels are: neighbor 1 (distance 1.2, label = 'A'), neighbor 2 (distance 1.5, label = 'B'), neighbor 3 (distance 1.8, label = 'A'), neighbor 4 (distance 2.5, label = 'B'), neighbor 5 (distance 3.0, label = 'A'). Taking only the 3 closest (distances 1.2, 1.5, 1.8 -> labels A, B, A), the majority vote is 2 votes for 'A' and 1 for 'B', so k-NN classifies P as 'A'. If k were changed to 5, all five neighbors would vote (3 'A' vs 2 'B'), still giving 'A' here — but in general, the choice of k can change the predicted class, which is why k is a hyperparameter to tune via cross-validation.",
