      overview:
        "Developing an ML-based application goes beyond training an accurate model — it requires building a reliable pipeline that takes the model from a research notebook to a production system that real users depend on, and that remains trustworthy over time. Once a model is trained and validated, it must be served (made available to make predictions on new inputs, often via an API or embedded in an app) as part of an inference pipeline. Because the real world changes, deployed models are subject to model drift — a gradual degradation in performance as the live data distribution diverges from the data the model was originally trained on (for example, a spam filter losing accuracy as spammers invent new tactics). To catch this, teams monitor deployed models for drift and performance degradation, and plan for retraining and versioning so that improved or updated models can replace stale ones safely. Beyond technical robustness, responsible deployment requires attention to fairness, bias, and explainability: a model trained on biased data can produce biased (and potentially harmful or discriminatory) predictions, and stakeholders often need to understand WHY a model made a particular prediction, especially in high-stakes domains such as healthcare, lending, or criminal justice. Major application domains that bring these concerns together include computer vision (AI that understands images and video, e.g., face recognition), natural language processing / NLP (AI that understands and generates human language, e.g., translation, chatbots), and robotics (AI controlling physical agents that sense and act in the real world).",
